description.narrative:
The structural upgrades completed include:
1) installation of two new outlets and three new taps (for a total of three water collection points);
2) reconstruction of the spring’s filtration system to prevent the dispensing of murky water during the rainy season, including the construction of a gravel filter and steel decantation tank;
3) addition of a service manhole/hatch for tank maintenance;
4) addition a sludge valve to clean naturally occurring sedimentary build-up once a week; and,
5) widening of the spring’s box enclosure and installing tiles to prevent algae growth.

In order to sustain the functionality of this spring for years to come, Lifeline also trained a nine-person Water User Committee (WUC) from Barapwo Te Dam to perform oversight and maintenance (O&amp;M) tasks, such as collecting water user fees for a community maintenance fund and reporting functionality issues to a local mechanic. To improve sanitation and hygiene conditions around the water point, Lifeline trained 48 community members on proper handwashing techniques and the dangers of water borne diseases, and established a two-person Village Health Team (VHT) to lead the community in upholding standards and best practices for good health and hygiene.
